Huh?
<griffon>KeyserSoze-ttyp2[94]~$ rpm -qf `which ifconfig`
net-tools-1.46-1
From Changes.txt:
- Net-tools              1.45                    ; hostname -V
> mkswap/swapon, and several other things are outdated.
<griffon>KeyserSoze-ttyp2[97]~$ rpm -qf `which swapon`
mount-2.8a-2
- Mount                  2.7l                    ; mount --version
This is from a pretty vanilla RedHat 5.2 setup.  Either Redhat *is* almost
2.2 ready or someone needs to updates Changes.txt.  Are you sure your
install is botched?
> /etc/rc.d/init.d/kerneld doesn't use kmod when available.
True, this is a stupid thing that Redhat should have fixed ages ago.  At
least it doesn't *break* anything since kerneld won't load in 2.2.
> /etc/nsswitch.conf misbehaves in 2.1+.
Don't have any experience, positive or negative, with this
> Red Hat 5.2 is not 2.2-ready.
I'd say it's "close enough"...the only thing I've had to update is dhcpcd
and I don't even think there *is* a dhcpcd which works with both 2.0 and 2.2.
